<subSubSection id="A0E565E2FF9FFFE3FE201EA68685B7AC" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="E8403669FF9FFFE3FE201EA6863DB6CD" blockId="8.[441,873,1195,1222]" box="[441,873,1195,1222]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">
<heading id="B3088105FF9FFFE3FE201EA6863DB6CD" box="[441,873,1195,1222]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FE201EA6863DB6CD" authority="(Draparnaud, 1805)" baseAuthorityName="Draparnaud" baseAuthorityYear="1805" box="[441,873,1195,1222]" class="Gastropoda" family="Physidae" genus="Physella" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FE201EA68720B6CD" bold="true" box="[441,628,1195,1222]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Physella acuta</emphasis>
(Draparnaud, 1805)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF9FFFE3FF591EEC8685B7AC" blockId="8.[160,1156,1249,1447]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">
The second globally invasive snail species, 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FD381EEC87ACB6F1" baseAuthorityName="Draparnaud" baseAuthorityYear="1805" box="[673,760,1249,1274]" class="Gastropoda" family="Physidae" genus="Physella" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FD381EEC87ACB6F1" box="[673,760,1249,1274]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">P. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to the Nearctic bioregion, but has been spread through aquaculture, ornamental aquatic plants and the aquarium trade over much of the world. 
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF9FFFE3FD8B1F2B863BB734" box="[530,879,1318,1343]" collectorName="We" location="St" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" specimenCount="1">
<collectorName id="450A53BFFF9FFFE3FD8B1F2B8762B734" box="[530,566,1318,1343]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">We</collectorName>
found it commonly on 
<location id="ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FCCF1F2B863BB734" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF9FFFE2FE201EA686B6B37C:ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FCCF1F2B863BB734" box="[854,879,1318,1343]" name="St" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">St</location>
</materialsCitation>
. 
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF9FFFE3FCE41F2B8104B78E" location="Crown" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="West Bay">
Thomas in ornamental fishponds at private residences, a ghut near a plant nursery, in artificial impoundments, and ditches (
<location id="ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FEA81F618428B78E" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF9FFFE2FE201EA686B6B37C:ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FEA81F618428B78E" box="[305,380,1388,1413]" name="Crown" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" stateProvince="West Bay">Crown</location>
<collectingRegion id="2A3BF88BFF9FFFE3FE1D1F6184F8B78E" box="[388,428,1388,1413]" country="Cayman Islands" name="West Bay" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Bay</collectingRegion>
ditch), and in highly polluted waters associated with ghuts
</materialsCitation>
. 
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF9FFFE3FBC21F618699B7AC" collectorName="It" location="Caribbean Islands" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="West Bay">
<collectorName id="450A53BFFF9FFFE3FBC21F61813EB78E" box="[1115,1130,1388,1413]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">It</collectorName>
is common throughout the 
<location id="ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FE581F8387DCB7AC" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF9FFFE2FE201EA686B6B37C:ED2060B2FF9FFFE3FE581F8387DCB7AC" box="[449,648,1422,1447]" name="Caribbean Islands" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" stateProvince="West Bay">Caribbean Islands</location>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9FFFE3FD0C1F838690B7AC" author="Harry HW &amp; Hubendick B" box="[661,964,1422,1447]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" pagination="1 - 77" refId="ref25430" refString="Harry HW, Hubendick B. 1964. The freshwater pulmonate Mollusca of Puerto Rico. K Vet O Vitterh Samh Handl. 9 (5): 1 - 77." type="journal article" year="1964">Harry and Hubendick 1964</bibRefCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A0E565E2FF9FFFE2FF391FDB86B6B37C" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="808" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" type="description">
<paragraph id="E8403669FF9FFFE3FF391FDB847BB7FB" blockId="8.[160,1156,1494,1728]" box="[160,303,1494,1520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FF391FDB847BB7FB" authorityName="Rafinesque" authorityYear="1815" box="[160,303,1494,1520]" class="Gastropoda" family="Planorbidae" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FF391FDB847BB7FB" bold="true" box="[160,303,1494,1520]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Planorbidae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF9FFFE2FF391FF786B6B37C" blockId="8.[160,1156,1494,1728]" lastBlockId="9.[160,1155,142,375]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="808" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">
Three genera of Planorbids were encountered in our surveys. This family is medically important as some species are intermediate hosts for human parasites (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9FFFE3FC441C108123B43D" author="Barbosa FS" box="[989,1143,1565,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" refId="ref22319" refString="Barbosa FS. 1995. Topicos em Malacologia Medica. Rio de Janiero (BRA): Editora Fiocruz; p. 314." type="journal volume" year="1995">Barbosa 1995</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FF391C3287ABB453" authority="(Richards and Ferguson, 1962)" baseAuthorityName="Richards and Ferguson" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[160,767,1599,1624]" class="Gastropoda" family="Bulinidae" genus="Plesiophysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hubendicki">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FF391C3284CCB453" box="[160,408,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Plesiophysa hubendicki</emphasis>
(Richards and Ferguson, 1962)
</taxonomicName>
is only known from Puerto Rico. 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FF391C6F8744B470" authority="(Say, 1818)" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[160,528,1634,1659]" class="Gastropoda" family="Planorbidae" genus="Biomphalaria" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="glabrata">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FF391C6F84DBB470" box="[160,399,1634,1659]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Biomphalaria glabrata</emphasis>
(Say, 1818)
</taxonomicName>
, the key intermediate host of the human parasitic blood fluke 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FF461C888725B495" authority="Sambon, 1907" authorityName="Sambon" authorityYear="1907" box="[223,625,1669,1694]" class="Trematoda" family="Schistosomatidae" genus="Schistosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostomida" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="mansoni">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9FFFE3FF461C88849CB495" box="[223,456,1669,1694]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="807">Schistosoma mansoni</emphasis>
Sambon, 1907
</taxonomicName>
(Platyhelminthes: 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9FFFE3FCA61C8886EDB495" authorityName="Rudolphi" authorityYear="1808" box="[831,953,1669,1694]" class="Trematoda" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="class">Trematoda</taxonomicName>
), is widespread in the Neotropics and reported from the Lesser Antilles (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9FFFE3FC9B1CAA8111B4CB" author="Hewitt R &amp; Willingham AL" box="[770,1093,1703,1728]" pageId="8" pageNumber="807" pagination="24" refId="ref25545" refString="Hewitt R, Willingham AL. 2019. Status of schistosomiasis elimination in the Caribbean region. Trop Med Infect Dis. 4 (1): 24. doi: 10.3390 / tropicalmed 4010024." type="journal article" year="2019">Hewitt and Willingham 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The congeneric 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9EFFE2FE871A83877AB2AC" authority="(Pfeiffer, 1848)" baseAuthorityName="Pfeiffer" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[286,558,142,167]" class="Gastropoda" family="Planorbidae" genus="Biomphalaria" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="albicans">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9EFFE2FE871A8384DAB2AC" box="[286,398,142,167]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="808">B. albicans</emphasis>
(Pfeiffer, 1848)
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from all the Greater and most of the Lesser Antilles as well (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9EFFE2FE051ABC8792B2C1" author="Harry HW &amp; Hubendick B" box="[412,710,177,202]" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" pagination="1 - 77" refId="ref25430" refString="Harry HW, Hubendick B. 1964. The freshwater pulmonate Mollusca of Puerto Rico. K Vet O Vitterh Samh Handl. 9 (5): 1 - 77." type="journal article" year="1964">Harry and Hubendick 1964</bibRefCitation>
). Neither of these species were encountered in our surveys, which agrees with the historical absence of schistosomiasis for the 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF9EFFE2FBC91AD981D6B2E6" box="[1104,1154,212,237]" name="Virgin Islands" pageId="9" pageNumber="808">USVI</collectingCountry>
territory (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9EFFE2FE9C1AFB8715B304" author="Hewitt R &amp; Willingham AL" box="[261,577,246,271]" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" pagination="24" refId="ref25545" refString="Hewitt R, Willingham AL. 2019. Status of schistosomiasis elimination in the Caribbean region. Trop Med Infect Dis. 4 (1): 24. doi: 10.3390 / tropicalmed 4010024." type="journal article" year="2019">Hewitt and Willingham 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The genus 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9EFFE2FD561AFB863DB304" authorityName="P. Fischer &amp; Crosse" authorityYear="1880" box="[719,873,246,271]" class="Gastropoda" family="Planorbidae" genus="Drepanotrema" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9EFFE2FD561AFB863DB304" box="[719,873,246,271]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="808">Drepanotrema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has five species reported for Puerto Rico, St. Thomas, and St. Croix (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9EFFE2FDC61B1486C7B339" author="Ferguson FF &amp; Richards CS" box="[607,915,281,306]" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" pagination="391 - 395" refId="ref24776" refString="Ferguson FF, Richards CS. 1963. Fresh-water mollusks of Puerto Rico and the U. S Virgin Islands Trans Am Microsc Soc. 82: 391 - 395. doi: 10.2307 / 3224199." type="journal article" year="1963">Ferguson and Richards 1963</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9EFFE2FC041B148582B35E" author="Harry HW &amp; Hubendick B" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" pagination="1 - 77" refId="ref25430" refString="Harry HW, Hubendick B. 1964. The freshwater pulmonate Mollusca of Puerto Rico. K Vet O Vitterh Samh Handl. 9 (5): 1 - 77." type="journal article" year="1964">Harry and Hubendick 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF9EFFE2FF781B3184C0B35E" author="Muchmore WB" box="[225,404,316,341]" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" pagination="30 - 38" refId="ref27570" refString="Muchmore WB. 1993. List of terrestrial invertebrates of St. John, US Virgin Islands (exclusive of Acarina and Insecta), with some records of freshwater species. Caribb J Sci. 29 (1 - 2): 30 - 38." type="journal article" year="1993">Muchmore 1993</bibRefCitation>
), but we did not encounter it is our surveys. 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF9EFFE2FCE11B318146B35E" authorityName="P. Fischer &amp; Crosse" authorityYear="1880" box="[888,1042,316,341]" class="Gastropoda" family="Planorbidae" genus="Drepanotrema" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="9" pageNumber="808" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF9EFFE2FCE11B318146B35E" box="[888,1042,316,341]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="808">Drepanotrema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in great need of revision, and the species are not reliably separated by morphology.
</paragraph>
